         "text": "### Introduction\n\nShimashki, like the city of Awan, are localities that, despite not yet having had their location identified (<htcite0>), raise no doubts as to their existence, which leads us to a first reflection.",
         "source": [
            {
               "type": 1,
               "uuid": "c1a3a583-2fdd-4128-ac2e-fef02c089b04",
               "text": "Hinz, W.",
               "page": "pp. 69 - 70",
               "date_time": {
                  "type": "gregory",
                  "year": "1972",
                  "month": "",
                  "day": ""
               }
            }
         ],
         "date_time": null,
         "isTable": false,
         "imgdesc": "",
         "format": "markdown",
         "PostMention": ""
      },
      {
         "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: On facts and poems</b><br /><br />How can we differentiate whether something written millennia ago is a historical fact or a poem?</div></div></center></p>",
         "source": null,
         "date_time": null,
         "isTable": false,
         "imgdesc": "",
         "format": "html",
         "PostMention": ""
      },
      {
         "text": "#### Archaeological evidence\n\nThe evidence for Shimashki is not abundant, but it exists. Most likely, the rise of the Shimashki dynasty occurred as a result of the fall of Awan (<htcite0>).\n\nHowever, the few available pieces of evidence are considered historical facts, such as the battle between Ibbi-Sin, king of Ur, and Lurak-luhhan, king of Shimashki, in the year <htdate0> (<htcite1>; <htcite2>).\n\n#### Spelling\n\nIn this text, we will work with the Shimashki dynasty (<htcite3>; <htcite4>; <htcite5>). However, in one of the works we are studying, the dynasty is mentioned as *Simashki* (<htcite6>).\n\nBecause we have no knowledge of the original language, we adopt the spelling most commonly used by scholars of the region (<htcite7>).",
         "source": [
            {
               "type": 1,
               "uuid": "c1a3a583-2fdd-4128-ac2e-fef02c089b04",
               "text": "Hinz, W.",
