                  {
                     "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 2: He mentioned, then...</b><br /><br />After the conquest of Babylon, in <htdate0>, a cylinder was produced for Cyrus (<b>Figure 2</b>) with some information, from which we highlight, for this study, the following excerpt (<htcite0>):<br /><br /><i>...I am Cyrus, king of the world, great king, mighty king, king of Babylon, king of the lands of Sumer and Akkad, king of the four quarters of the universe, son of Cambyses, great king, king of Anshan, descendant of Teispes, great king, king of Anshan...</i><br /><br />With these phrases, let us make some reflections:<br /><br />Would Cyrus have only mentioned some ancestors because it was impossible to create a list going back to the first kings of Anshan?<br /><br />Is there any possibility of linking Cyrus to the kings of Anshan and Shimashki?<br /><br />Before these questions, did you happen to suppose that Cyrus could be related to the ancient kings of Anshan and Shimashki?<br /><br />Between <htdate1> and <htdate2>, there is an interval of 1,499 years. Assuming that generations occur every 30 years, that means that if Cyrus were to list his ancestors back to that time, his cylinder would have approximately 49 generations. Considering that we are only beginning the study, do you understand that there would be 49 well-documented kings between Cyrus and the kings of Anshan from the time of Girnamme?<br ><br />Do you think there is a possibility that someone invented names to connect the first Persian emperor, Cyrus, to historical or imaginary kings of the past, with the aim of creating an identity for him?<br /><br />If someone had created that list, would you accept it? Would you say it is wrong without researching? Or would you look for all the kings to verify what is fact and what is imaginary?<br /><br />Since Cyrus was the “king of the universe”, why did he only mention nearby regions in the sequence? Would it not be better to mention all the regions of the world? Or even other planets, to leave no doubt?</div></div></center>",
                     "source": [
                        {
                           "type": 0,
                           "uuid": "73cc1d07-b9c6-4c6d-894d-17cdf822bc44",
                           "text": "O Cilindro de Ciro",
                           "page": "",
                           "date_time": {
